To make the data easier to work with later (i.e.instead of having to rewrite filters each time), I will create indicator variables and new columns to parse out the Category column. This is a relatively small data set so I am not too worried about increasing the number of columns.

Data Quirks

Some Cities/Category combinations have Population = NA (notably all of those have the category Owner: Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Householder). I am assuming these cities do not a people who identify with those ethnicities.

From my initial exploration (see Appendix for quick scratch work), I see that each age group was mutually exclusive but race was not (especially with the 2+ races). Therefore, there was double counting within race.

Programming Note

In terms of coding style, I will refrain from writing functions or loops so as to ensure each code chunk can be read and understood more or less independently of all the other code chunks. In addition, the plots used in this report will not be polished with title-cased axes titles as they are mostly intended for exploratory purposes. This will not be the most polished in terms of style.

df <- data %>%
  mutate(own_or_rent = ifelse(str_detect(Category, "Rent"), yes = "Rent", no = "Own"),
         age_group = str_extract(Category, "\\d{2}-(\\d{2})?"),
         totals = ifelse(str_detect(Category, "units"), yes = 1, no = 0), # geographical totals
         race = str_trim(str_extract(Category, 
                            "(?<=(Renter: |Owner: ))[:print:]+(?=(Household)[:alpha:]*)"))
  )

1 Growth Rate of Owner and Renter Populations

Here, I will use the Population who have renter or owner occupied units as the unit to measure growth. I define growth rate from 2006 to 2012 as the number of units in 2012 minus the number of units in 2006 taken as a percetage of the number of units in 2006.

I filtered to just the location of United States (which I assume provides the country-level aggregated value).

In addition to calculating the percent change since 2006, I also calculated the year over year percent change as well.

1.1 Owner Population - Growth Rate (2006 - 2012)

own_growth <- df %>% filter(totals == 1,
                         own_or_rent == "Own",
                         Location == "United States") %>%
  arrange(Year) %>%
  mutate(yoy_percent = 
           (Population - lag(Population, default = first(Population)))
         /lag(Population, default = first(Population))*100,
         percentchangefrom2006 = (Population - first(Population))/first(Population)*100)

print(own_growth %>% select(Year, Population, yoy_percent, percentchangefrom2006),
      row.names = FALSE)
# A tibble: 7  4

From 2006 to 2012, there was a -1.29% growth rate in owner-occupied units. So less people have owner-occupied units in 2012 than in 2006. Looking at the year-over-year growth rate reveal that apart from an increase between 2006 and 2007, there has been a steady decline of people with owner-occupied units.

That being said, there is still about double the amount of owner-occupied units than renter-occupied units.

# Rental Proportions
age_prop <- df %>% filter(!is.na(age_group),
              Location == "United States") %>%
  group_by(age_group, Year) %>%
  mutate(percent_rent = Population/sum(Population))

age_prop %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = percent_rent,
                       color = own_or_rent)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~age_group, nrow = 2) +
   theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 25, hjust = 1))

While this chart might be a little dense, it does illuminate the fact a few interesting ideas:

  1. the two youngset age groups (15-24) and (25-34) have a higher proportion of renters and buyers.For these two groups, the lines are also diverging, showing that over time, there seems to be an increase of the population with rental units.

  2. In the second row, particularly for the 65+ age group, there appears to be a stable renting/buying habit as the proportions have not changed at all over time for these age groups.

  3. For the middle age groups (especially with the 35-44 age group), there appears to be a trend of decreasing ownership and increasing rentalship. It is possible that after 2012, the proportion of renters could exceed the proprtion of buyers for these age groups.

I am interpreting this question as: what cities have seen the highest growth of renters between 2006 and 2012?

With that question in mind, the analysis is similar to what I did in the previous section. The conclusions will be limited since we only have thirty cities in this dataset.

Los Angeles is a city distinguished by many things: Hollywood, Beverley Hills, boardwalks and beaches. As of 2012, LA is also the only city (in a list of thirty major cities) that has a higher percentage of renters than homebuyers.

Between 2006 and 2012, renting increased with older age groups seeing the largest growth in renting. But age is not only correlated with more renting, but more home ownership as well. It is possible that this group is still staying at home with their parents.

Sunny Phoenix, Arizona saw the highest renter growth between 2006 and 2012. The Valley of the Sun, with its temperate weather famously (like the rest of Arizona) does not observe Daylight Savings Time. Blessed with abundant sunshine and warm weather, the city seems to be a great place to live. The population of 60-64 year old renters has nearly doubled between 2006 and 2012, making it the city with the second highest increase of 60-64 renter growth in the nation, just after Riverside, California.

Like most other large cities in the nation, Phoenix still has a higher number of homeowners than renters. However, the gap appears to be closing as the number of homeowners decrease over time and the number of renters increase. Renters appear to be increasing at a faster rate than homeownership is dropping.

Although usually a tourist destination, many people seem to be increasingly calling Las Vegas home.

6 US Housing Crisis

The current US housing system is among one of the largest dangers to the global economy. Worth trillions of dollars, the US housing market is the worlds largest asset class but the mortgage debt that powers this asset class is also the largest concentration of risk in the world. Why?

After the housing and financial crisis that transpired in 2008, the US government stepped in to guarantee housing mortgages in order to protect investors from defaulting homeowners. As a legacy of that system, the government currently underwrites a majority of the housing mortgages in the United States. It seems like a win-win situation: investors get a low-risk investment and homeowners have access to an affordable mortgage, funded by taxpayers. Since the government is able to promise such low fees, private banks and financial institutions are unable to compete and have since mostly withdrawn from the mortgage game. That means US taxpayers are shouldering most of risk and burden involved, should homeowners decide to default.

To address the imbalance of risk and reward, economists have suggested that the US government charge a higher fee so that the fee matches the risk involved. However, Congress is gridlocked and unable to enact change especially change that will make it more difficult for prospective homeowners to buy a house.
